@author "Mathew Wilson"
@wordwrap

## $VER: Hints and Tips v1.00 (12.03.97)

@node Tips "Hints and Tips"

	@{b}HINTS AND TIPS@{ub}

The following is a set of guidlines that will help you when using On-Time.

·  ALWAYS use a @{"Classification" link Config_GeneralNameClasses} system when naming your Events and Tasks!

·  Set the Event and Task Filter strings to "Single" and activate the Filters then select Save Config from the Settings menu. Now whenever you run On-Time the lists will display Events and Tasks for today.

·  Try and familiarise yourself with the different ways of entering @{"dates" link Dates}. This will often speed things up a little.

·  If you want to alter a Date by one day, select the Date Object(gadget) and use the up and down cursor keys. Holding down Shift at the same time will increment/decrement in months. The same goes for Time Objects.

·  Remember that the Calendar Windows each have a unique ID so you can snap-shot their positions in the way you normally do with MUI windows.

·  You can hide or show the Date Objects in Calendar Windows by pressing the "delete" key when the window is activate.

·  The Event and Task Filter Dates can be altered by double-clicking on a day in a Calendar Window.

·  You can run On-Time with just it's window open by selecting the Iconify Mode option in the configuration.

·  On-Time uses @{"drag-&-drop" link UsingDrag&Drop} for a variety of things.

·  If you want to Save or Use without quiting then use the pull-down menus.

·  As with Alarmist and Locate, there is an icon tool-type "STARTUP_SCRIPT" that allows for an ARexx script to be performed at run-time.
@endnode

@node FilterExamples "Hints and Tips"

	@{b}Examples of using Filters@{ub}

The Event and Task Display Lists, in the main window, can be configured to display whatever you like, instead of the whole list. It is important to understand how the filter system works so you can gain the most from the program.

The following provides examples of Event and Task Filters so you can get an idea of how to use them. You must have the Filters activated via their Check Mark gadget. Of course, you may use them in combination with each other - this is the whole purpose of the Filter List. They are only examples and are not by any means a definitive list of possiblities!

@{fg highlight}Show All Events/Tasks for a specific day.@{fg text}
@{b}Filter Date:@{ub}   Relevant day, eg. 'today'
@{b}Filter String:@{ub} 'day 1'

@{fg highlight}Show All Events/Tasks for a specific week.@{fg text}
@{b}Filter Date:@{ub}   Any date within the relevant week, eg. 'today'
@{b}Filter String:@{ub} 'week'

Note: The 'week' parameter aligns itself to the first day of the Localised week.

@{fg highlight}Show only Events/Tasks of a certain 'name type'@{fg text}
When naming events you are encouraged to use a name classification system, eg. "TV: Babylon 5", "Birthday: Me". This will enable you to use the following example to show groups/or types of events. 

@{b}Filter Date:@{ub}   Will display events in order of when they next occur in relation to this date, unless another filter parameter overrides this.
@{b}Filter String:@{ub} 'matchname TV:#?'

All events beginning with 'TV:' will be displayed.

@{fg highlight}Filter out Events/Tasks of a certain 'name type'@{fg text}
@{b}Filter Date:@{ub}   As previous example.
@{b}Filter String:@{ub} 'mn ~(TV:#?)

Filter out (do not show) any events that begin with 'TV:'
This is just like the previous example but shows another way of Pattern Matching. You AmigaDOS manual gives you a full description of Pattern Matching. Read it!

@{fg highlight}Show all old Events for next week'@{fg text}
ie. Show every day next week, displaying when old events occur.

@{b}Filter Date:@{ub}   Some date next week, eg. datestring = 'week'
@{b}Filter String:@{ub} "week old'

Note: This works the same for the Event Filter switch 'Future' and 'State'.
      You may also do this with Tasks using the 'overdue' and 'future' switches.

@{fg highlight}Show all events for the present month, but don't show TV events'@{fg text}
@{b}Filter Date:@{ub}   'today' will suffice, although not really important.
@{b}Filter String:@{ub} 'matchmonth march matchyear 97 matchname ~(tv:#?)'
            or 'mm 3 my 1997 mn ~(tv:#?)

@{fg highlight}Show all events for the present month that occur on a Wednesday, but don't show TV events'@{fg text}
@{b}Filter Date:@{ub}   'today' will suffice, although not really important.
@{b}Filter String:@{ub} 'matchmonth march matchyear 1997 matchweekday wednesday matchname ~(tv:#?)'
            or 'mm 3 my 1997 mw wed mn ~(tv:#?)

@endnode

